'''Kuchi Shrine''' (??????, ???????) is a {{ill|lt=shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Hy?go Prefecture|Q130290|qid=Q130290|1=Hyōgo Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Nishinomiya|Q243853|qid=Q243853|1=Nishinomiya}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Shikinai Sh?sha|Q134917287|qid=Q134917287|1=Shikinai Shosha}} listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmy?ch?|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, and its former shrine rank was {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q90139226|lt=Ken-sha|1=Ken-sha}}.

It enshrines {{ill|lt=Kukunochi|Q10749920|qid=Q10749920|lt=Kukunochi-no-Kami|1=Kukunochi}}, {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|qid=Q272993|lt=Takesoku Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}, and {{ill|qid=Q505469|lt=Kushinadahime|Q505469|qid=Q505469|qid=Q505469|lt=Kushinadahime-no-Mikoto|1=Kushinadahime}}.

=== History ===
The founding date is unknown, but tradition says it began when the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kukuchi clan|1=UNKNOWN}}, descendants of {{ill|lt=?biko no Mikoto|Q11435420|qid=Q11435420|1=Ōhiko-no-Mikoto}}, a prince of {{ill|lt=Emperor K?gen|Q333572|qid=Q333572|1=Emperor Kōgen}}, worshipped the ancestral deity of trees Kukunochi-no-Kami (Kukunohachi-no-Kami) as their tutelary deity. In the winter of Taika 3, timber from this shrine's area was used for imperial works during Emperor K?toku's visit to Arima, and because of its excellent quality the mountain name "K?chiyama" was bestowed. During the {{ill|lt=J?gan (Japan)|Q1075635|qid=Q1075635|lt=J?gan|1=Jōgan}} era, Takesoku Susanoo-no-Mikoto and Kushinadahime-no-Mikoto were jointly enshrined, and the shrine was called Tenn?-g? and Gion Gozu Tenn?. In April 1929, it was promoted to prefectural shrine.

